This is me every time I start making a costume. I promise myself I will record each step from start to finish... then I forget halfway through! 

Here are tips I use to help me record diy projects: 

1- You don't need to record the 🌟 ENTIRE 🌟 thing. Short 30s clips of footage from each part from two angles is normally more than enough.

2- Get different angles! 👀 I like to try and do a side version and a front on version. It helps break up the footage so that not everything looks the same. Especially when it's something where it's hard to tell what you're doing (like sewing) 🧵

3- Remember aspect ratios. Do you plan on uploading this on 9:16 and 16:9? Record farther out, so if you need to crop in, you can! 🎥

4- Write down all the steps in the process and then cross each one out after you get that footage. I know this one seems like, duh! But it's helpful 😂

Ok, now record all your progress so I can watch it 😈

☕️ La Posteria Praiano @laposteriapraiano

It was the most lovely hotel I have ever seen in my life. The plants on the side of the building actually grow into the terrace bar. We were even lucky enough to have dinner at Zass

Your opinion is none of my business 🥰

I have always struggled a lot with mean comments. I'm not built for rejection, which makes it hard to deal with sometimes. 

I joke that the internet has told me things I need to be insecure about that I never in my life was before. Or that they have stolen joy from me by saying harsh things when I'm excited...

But the more I grow, the more I learn that the only path forward is the one that you make, and the one will make you happy with who you are at the end of it.

So be weird, dress in cosplay in public, make stupid faces, get weird looks and mean comments... and just be the you that only you can be 💗

Don't make these cosplay mistakes! Tips below ⬇️

I was working a short turnaround for this @nikke_global cosplay for @danielledenicola and literally just kept making the simplest of sewing errors 🥲

1- Sticky Fabric. I use a special sewing machine foot called a Teflon foot. It is much less likely to stick to your fabric and cause it to catch. BUT sometimes that isn't enough. So you can also get Tear-Away stabilizer (or just use tissue like toilet paper) if you are working with a tricky fabric like a pleather.

2- The symbols on her pants were not high res enough for me to pull out using photoshop or illustrator- so I used my iPad and procreate to draw the general shapes- then put it into the @cricut design space. Worked like a charm!

3- Ironing! ALWAYS use a drop cloth. Literally, don't be cocky like me and think you can do it without. I've ruined so many things this way. I just use a 100% cotton fabric and place it on top of whatever I'm ironing, so that way, the actual iron never touches my fashion fabric. You can also use musslin!

4- Iron on Vinyl. For this project, I was using a sports flex iron on by cricut- which you need to use a "cool pull" for. This means you heat the vinyl on the top AND bottom of the fabric so it really adheres and then wait for it to completely cool before you pull it off. I was impatient and also didn't iron it while it was slightly stretched - so it just started to come off, and I had to redo it. 

Let me know if this is helpful and if you want more in progress cosplay tutorial bts content!!!

I've been cosplaying for years now, and these are the things I wish I knew when I started:

1- If you make your own cosplay, it's ok it's not perfect. With so many cosplayers, now it's impossible not to judge yourself against more experienced crafters when you are starting out. But don't let others experience deter or discourage you from starting! 

2- Try not to skip steps in the creation process. My adhd makes this really hard since I want the dopamine of starting the costume and  finishing the project... not so much. But I regret so many years of costumes that i just can't wear anymore since I skipped steps to finish faster! 

3- ATTEMPT not to care about what others think. (I use attempt because it's hard not to) Cosplaying can be incredibly vulnerable- especially because we are putting our passions, money, and time into it. And the internet WILL be mean about it. I really wish it wasn't the case, but they can absolutely just be nasty. Don't make yourself smaller because you are worried about them (or even about the people you know irl) You'll regret it.

4- Buying a costume does not make you less of a cosplayer. We don't need any "back in my day" people trying to gatekeep cosplay by making it creation elitism. If you get the joy out of just wearing the cosplay and don't want to make it- it's fine. 

5- If you're going to spend money on any part of your cosplay, make it the wig. Wigs imo are the MOST important since that are right by your face. A good wig can elevate a bad costume and a bad wig can make a good cosplay look subpar. 

These are just things I wish I personally knew when I started, let me know if you want a video with all the stores i use for costimes and the tutorials I follow! 

#howtocosplay #cosplaydiy #cosplaytutorial

Want to know the secret to feeling more confident in cosplay? Or just building up the courage to actually put on a costume? 

I got you 👏

One of the first conventions I went to, I actually locked myself in the hotel bathroom crying because I was so nervous. I remember sitting on the tub edge thinking

 "What if people make fun of me?" 

"What if no one likes it?"

"What if people think I'm weird?"

And an entire slew of other negative things. Because it's a lot to put yourself out their in such a vulnerable way! So if you're nervous or one of those people who comment, " I wish i had your confidence!" Here are my secrets.

1- Do it afraid! Life is full of scary moments. But I know personally I regret the things I didn't try in life. Sometimes, it just takes that initial moment of being scared before someone compliments you or asks for your photo or likes your post for you to start to realize it wasn't all that scary in the first place. 

2- Actively go out of your way to lift other cosplayers up! This one is important because not only does it start to put you in the positive mindset for yourself, but it helps foster a community where others will also want to lift you up. Nothing builds my self-confidence more than someone telling me something nice.

3- Don't be mean to yourself. We are our own worst critics, and it's so easy to want to put yourself down before others have the chance. But we also need to be our own #1 fans, even if we're just faking it! Since faking it one day will eventually lead to believing it later.

4- Be prepared. I feel significantly more confident when I know I have a solution for things that could go wrong! I keep a sewing kit in my car, Bobby pins in my purse, and at least two types of glue on me at all times. I also make sure I have an accessible jacket for if I want to take a break to recenter. (It's not being messy --- it's being prepared xD)

What are your tips for feeling more confident? 

#cosplaytips #peronacosplay

Some of these are going to surprise you 🙈

But save this reel first (it helps me, and you can then revist this later, too!) 

1- BLOCK PEOPLE. And I'm not just talking about people who say something mean in your comments. I'm talking about those friends and family members who make you nervous they will judge you. If you are too scared to post your most authentic self online because of people in your life, just block them so they don't have to see, and you don't have to worry. 🥰 I have my cosplay one and my personal @reaganexplores for this reason! 

2- You absolutely can do trendy cosplays, but don't forget to make time for things you really like that aren't as popular. I did Velma before she was everywhere (oh man, I sound old), and she was one of the first cosplays that started to grow my account. And i really just wanted to do a fun friend cosplay with @ashlynnedae at the time!!

3- This brings me to my next point, which might be controversial. Don't feel bad about wanting followers. More followers absolutely do NOT make you a better person or superior than others, but I spend thousands of dollars and hours on my costumes. I want people to see them. My entire family can attest to the fact that the second I finish or make anything, I walk around my house showing them - I've got to be the annoying one in the family group chat. But it's because I'm so EXCITED to share the thing I love with others and for them to be excited back. It fuels me 💖

4- Four costume changes in a day at a convention is too much yall. I get it's so exciting to want to pack as much into the day as you can, but you end up spending all day just changing. I'll give you two cosplays a day! Your day costume then night costume (for those lucky cosplayers who still have the energy)

5- Contradictory to my last point: Don't let others tell you how to cosplay. Sure, we all say "no more con crunch," but some of my most treasured memories are from making things last minute with my friends. Or "don't use hot glue and safety pins." Is it the most ideal? No! But half my closures are just safety pins still... if it works, it works!

How YOU cosplay, is the correct way to cosplay ❤️

🛑 How to make money as a cosplayer!!! 

This is the number one question you guys have been asking me! So save this video and share it with a friend (we all want to quit our day jobs right?) 

1- Commissions 🧵 actually making a costume, prop, wig, 3d prints, or anything else for other people! Normally, you need to be a more advanced level of crafter! I only take commissions from people who live by me and are referred to me since I still need to fit sewing patterns on a physical person!

2- Patterns and Tutorials 🧡 This is not necessarily a physical product, but putting up patterns of things you have made so that other people can make the same thing! (Like how I got this Zelda pattern from @indigo_jinjo who sells their sewing patterns). I see this mostly with sewing or foam patterns, STL files, or full written tutorials on how to make costumes.

3- Photo Sets 📸  while this can be of the adult variety, it doesn't have to! I don't do anything spicy, but I will sell sets of full costumes since I seldom post all the pictures I have. But if you are down with being spicy- it can be really lucrative! But know it isn't just easy money,  It's really hard work and will sometimes make the #4 harder.

4- Brand Deals 💰 I love working with brands that align with my audience. Typically, you either are reviewing a product or game to raise awareness or my favorite way, making a costume to wear on your socials or at an event (so brands, If you need cosplayers... hit me up 🙏🥺) --- for this, you need good engagement (the reasons I'm always asking for you to comment), and for most things (not all!), you should be brand friendly.

5- Conventions/Events 🥳 I love working with companies to cosplay at their booths! It's super fun to take pictures and meet people. You can also attend as a guest to sell prints and other items. I normally will also offer to host panels (I have a couple I love doing), judge or mc the costume contest as I want to make sure im offering a good value back to conventions in return for them paying me to come!

Let me know if this helpful & if you have questions, drop them in the comments. This is not an all-inclusive list bc I ran out of room to type it all!

The most common question I get asked is how to go viral... and my answer is a lot of times disappointing...

First, to go viral, you really need people to engage with your content en mass (which is why we are always asking you to like, comment, share our posts... like this one 🙏 send it to your friend!)

BUT what people don't tell you are all the reasons why consistent growth is SO MUCH better than virality, and here is why:

1- People who follow you from a viral post are NORMALLY just there for whatever content is in that post. The second you post something else, people are nit interested- its a quick way to railroad your account. I am actually considering starting an entire new clock account since my post that went viral didn't have me in it. I got millions of views and tons of followers, but afterward, my engagement and watch time TANKED since people were not there for me.

2- When people are not there for your normal content, they don't engage with your future content. And when they don't engage- platforms think that you are not posting quality content and start showing it less. This means that everything you post starts getting LESS exposure - and even can cause you to not be able to gain more followers after.

3- Viral brings out the mean normies. 9/10, the comments on viral posts are full of hateful and downright nasty comments. (If you leave a mean comment... tell me why. Seriously, I'm so curious as to why.) It's like the big numbers make it ok for people to say whatever not nice thing comes to their head? Where as when you have steady growth that is gaining numbers over time- people typically are their because they like YOU and so are much nicer.

4- Your worth isn't based on your numbers (im trying yo learn this one, too 😅) it's ok to post something and have it not get a TON of views. One of my top posts was actually my lowest in views for two months before the algo found it - and then it had a ton! Just post what you want, and other people who resonate will follow. Don't chase virality and let your content suffer for it.

Ultimately, the goal is CONSISTENT GROWTH,finding your target audience of people who love YOU and your content. You got this 🥰

Ok, there is actually a lot of good cosplay advice 😅 so I'll share just a few of my favorites this time! 

Share with your friends so we can all have a positive 2024 🙏

1- Your cosplay doesn't have to be popular! It's easy to forget that cosplay isn't a popularity contest. At the end of the day, you should cosplay whatever brings you joy! (Literally, I'm wearing a book costume in this reel- shout out OUABH) 

2- You can cosplay popular things just because they are popular. Seriously, guys, stop gatekeeping. Wanna cosplay something because everyone else is. GO AHEAD! Sometimes, it's fun to feel like part of a bigger community. Don't let people steal that joy! 🥰

3- it's alright to want more followers. Just don't make it the lynch pin of your self-worth! I work for hundreds of hours on my costumes sometimes - OF COURSE - I want as many people to see my hard work as possible. I actually make my entire family look at everything I make through the entire process. "Look at it." It's basically my catchphrase 😅

4- Your cosplay is just as important even if you don't have the followers. Again, followers help you get things like brand deals and income - they do not define what is good craftsmanship, artistic view, or work ethic! They will never make you better than someone or someone better than you 💖

Don't make the same mistakes as me ⚠️🙈

It's actually multiple things!! So I'll break them down...

1- Not having my email easily available!!! It should be everywhere!! I've had people tell me they didn't put it up because they thought they were too small when I was trying to hire them for a campaign. You're NEVER too small. Honestly, if you are too hard to reach, you will be passed over. PUT YOUR EMAIL EVERYWHERE! 

2- Focusing on Followers instead of Engagement. 99.9% of brands higher and pay based off engagement, not followers. If you have 1 million followers but only 10 people watch your video... that isn't a good investment. Engagement will always be more important than follower count.

3- Not having a clear audience. For example- if you are a cosplayer, are you speaking to other cosplayers? Are you speaking to people who like cosplay but don't do it themselves? Are you talking to people who like anime? Video games? Comics? These are all different groups! If you only do comic book cosplays but are trying to get collaborations with anime companies- it probably isn't going to happen. Because your audience doesn't care about anime! Pick an audience and understand who they are and what they like!

4-  Not having a Media Kit or EPK. This is something that has who you are, examples of work, and most importantly, all your statistics! So, how many followers on each platform, your average engagement rate per post, your audience demographics. Need help making one? Just comment below, and I'll send you a template!
